    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Afro-Cuban drums, generally single-headed and with nail tension, approximately cylindrical or barrel-shaped and open at the bottom; they are played with two drumsticks. For the snared double-headed cylindrical drums of the Yoruba people of Nigeria, see "bembes."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Tambores afrocubanos, generalmente de una sola cabeza y con tensión por tornillos, aproximadamente cilíndricos o en forma de barril y abiertos en la parte inferior; se tocan con dos baquetas. Para los tambores cilíndricos de dos cabezas con bordones del pueblo Yoruba de Nigeria, véa "bembe”.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Afro-Cubaanse trommen met enkel vel, met nagels opgespannen, cilinder- of tonvormig en open aan de onderzijde; bespeeld met twee trommelstokken. Zie 'bembes' Voor de besnaarde cilindertrommels met dubbel vel van de Yoruba in Nigeria.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>古巴黑人的單面鼓，通常為單鼓面，並以釘子調節鬆緊緊。近似圓柱狀或桶狀，底部有開口，以兩根鼓棒演奏。若指奈及利亞優魯巴人使用，裝有響弦的圓柱狀雙鼓面鼓，則參見「班比鼓」。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Afro-kubanische Trommel, gewöhnlich einfellig und mit Nagelspannung, annähernd zylindrisch oder fassförmig und am Boden offen, gespielt mit zwei Schlägeln. Für die zweifellige, zylindrische Schnarrtrommel der Yoruba aus Nigeria siehe "[Bembe (zweifellige Trommel)](300041773)".</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
